<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>flipping direction | Christine Bauer</title><link>https://christinebauer.eu/tag/flipping-direction/</link><atom:link href="https://christinebauer.eu/tag/flipping-direction/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><description>flipping direction</description><generator>Hugo Blox Builder (https://hugoblox.com)</generator><language>en-us</language><copyright>Â© 2023 Christine Bauer</copyright><lastBuildDate>Tue, 03 Jan 2023 02:00:06 +0200</lastBuildDate><image><url>https://christinebauer.eu/media/sharing.png</url><title>flipping direction</title><link>https://christinebauer.eu/tag/flipping-direction/</link></image><item><title>HICSS 2023 paper on conformity behavior in group decision-making</title><link>https://christinebauer.eu/post/20230103_hicss2023/</link><pubDate>Tue, 03 Jan 2023 02:00:06 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://christinebauer.eu/post/20230103_hicss2023/</guid><description>&lt;p>What a nice way to start a new year&amp;mdash;with a publication. &lt;a href="https://bruceferwerda.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Bruce Ferwerda&lt;/a> in on beautiful Maui ðŸŒº to present our joint HICSS 2023 paper on conformity behavior in group decision-making.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>In our work, we explored whether and how the ingroup favoritism manifests differently in terms of conformity behavior depending on the &amp;lsquo;flipping direction&amp;rsquo; (in favor or against an item). The results show that group inclusiveness does not play a role in the general tendency to conform. However, when it comes to a negative flipping direction (thus, deciding to conform with the group against an item), a higher feeling of group inclusiveness seems to play a role; yet, for individualist cultures only.
&lt;br>
